ce:section.ce:para:
According to the SEM images of CDs/NDs@Fe3O4@Ni (Appx. Fig. 7
                        ), nanoparticles were loaded onto the CDs/NDs@Fe3O4 substrate. Based on the EDX analysis (Appx. Fig. 8
                        ), CDs/NDs@Fe3O4@Ni has a composition of 47.8 wt% Fe, 22.5 wt% C and 3.8 wt% Ni. ICP-OES analysis revealed the actual metal composition of CDs/NDs@Fe3O4@Ni as 35.13 wt% Fe and 4.64 wt% Ni. Based on the above analyses and in accordance with the TEM image of CDs/NDs@Fe3O4@Ni (Fig. 3), nanoparticles were settled and assembled within the semi-reticulated assemblies of the reduced graphene oxide. Here, the metal oxide constituent (Fe3O4) controlled the Ni nanoparticles' distribution and morphology within the CDs/NDs@Fe3O4@Ni scaffold. Generally, metal oxide carriers interact with metal particles and can change their electronic properties which ultimately contributes to particles’ morphology determination, maintaining their dispersion, and higher catalytic activities.

The BET curves of CDs/NDs@Fe3O4@Ni were obtained by performing N2 adsorption-desorption process at 65 °C for 8 h. As indicated by the isotherms of nitrogen sorption, the adsorption capacity of the nano-catalyst is almost linear because the adsorption increases with pressure (Appx. Fig. 10
                        ). The BET experimental data of CDs/NDs@ Fe3O4@ Ni was summarized in Appx. Table 1
                        . In accordance with the table, the measurements carried out based on the BJH method (Appx. Fig. 11
                        ) revealed 131 m2/g cumulative adsorption surface area, 2.443 nm adsorption pore diameter and 0.173 cc/g cumulative adsorption pore volume (pores with diameters less than 265.64 nm at p/p0 = 0.992736) for the synthesized nano-catalyst.
